{{Infobox video game | title = BMX XXX | image = BMX XXX Coverart.png | developer = [[Z-Axis]] | publisher = [[AKA Acclaim]] | platforms = [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[GameCube]] | released = '''Xbox'''{{vgrelease|NA|November 12, 2002|EU|December 6, 2002}}'''PlayStation 2'''{{vgrelease|NA|November 19, 2002|EU|December 5, 2002}}'''GameCube'''{{vgrelease|NA|November 26, 2002|EU|February 7, 2003}} | genre = [[Sports game|Sports]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] }}
'''''BMX XXX''''' is a [[Sports game|sports]] [[video game]] developed by [[Z-Axis]] and published by [[Acclaim Entertainment]] under their AKA Acclaim label for the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[PlayStation 2]] and [[GameCube]]. While primarily a [[BMX]]-based [[action sports]] title, it earned most of its notoriety for containing [[nudity]], [[foul language]] and adult humor. The game allows the player to create female characters that are fully [[Toplessness|topless]] and view live-action video clips of real life [[stripper]]s, also with bare [[breasts]]. Consequently, ''BMX XXX'' was initially denied classification in Australia. In North America, while the game is available uncensored on the GameCube and Xbox, all naked breasts are covered in the PlayStation 2 version. While the adult content garnered a great deal of publicity for the game, it was almost entirely negative, and it was eventually released to mediocre reviews and poor sales.
==Production== ''BMX XXX'' builds on the earlier work done by Z-Axis on ''[[Dave Mirra Freestyle BMX]]'', their previous BMX title featuring and endorsed by professional [[BMX rider]] [[Dave Mirra]]. During development of the new game, publisher [[Acclaim Entertainment]] decided to style the game after a raunchy [[sex comedy]] movie. It is commonly believed that the origins of this decision came when Acclaim saw what was shaping up to be an extremely subpar game, and so, in an effort to salvage the time and money already invested in it, they decided to add the vulgar humor and naked women in an effort to muster up [[publicity]] and hopefully turn that into sales.<ref>{{cite web |author=IGN staff |title=E3 2002: Dave Mirra BMX XXX |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/22/e3-2002-dave-mirra-bmx-xxx |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=May 22, 2002 |accessdate=March 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325142434/http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/22/e3-2002-dave-mirra-bmx-xxx# |archive-date=2016-03-25 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref> When Mirra found out about the content in the game, he refused to [[Testimonial|endorse]] the product and took legal action against publisher [[Acclaim Entertainment|Acclaim]] in order to prevent any further implication of his involvement in the game.<ref name="videogames.yahoo.com">{{cite web |author=IGN staff |title=Dave Mirra Sues Acclaim |url=http://videogames.yahoo.com/news-1118429 |publisher=[[Yahoo! Games]] (IGN) |date=February 14, 2003 |accessdate=November 27, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109064437/http://videogames.yahoo.com/news-1118429 |archivedate=9 January 2008<!--DASHBot--> |deadurl=yes}}</ref> Mirra was successful in getting the courts to block Acclaim from using his name in association with the game, and the title was then shortened to its final name, ''BMX XXX''.<ref name="videogames.yahoo.com"/>
